  <content>
    <title>Tree Testing: Validate Information Architecture Before Building</title>

    <summary>Tree testing evaluates the findability of topics in a website's hierarchy. Users are given tasks and navigate a text-only version of the site structure (no design, no content) to find where they would expect the answer. It separates the validation of your information architecture from visual/interaction design, providing data-driven answers to IA debates.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Your navigation structure seems logical to your team. Users cannot find content even with search. Information architecture (IA) debates are based on opinions. You redesigned navigation and need to validate before building. Card sorting gave you structure but you have not tested it. Without tree testing, you end up with navigation based on org structure, findability problems discovered late, no data to resolve IA debates, and expensive redesigns after launch.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Validating a draft information architecture after card sorting and before visual design.</item>
        <item>Comparing two IA candidates (A/B trees) on real user findability data.</item>
        <item>Diagnosing why search analytics show high "no-result" or zero-click rates on category pages.</item>
        <item>Re-baselining IA after a major content reorg or merger of two product taxonomies.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Before any IA exists — start with card sorting.</item>
        <item>For visual/UX issues unrelated to navigation — usability testing fits better.</item>
        <item>For workflows with strong cross-linking and search dominance (no hierarchical paths to test).</item>
        <item>One-page apps and dashboards — too few branches for meaningful tree-test signal.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="tree-testing-vs-card-sorting">
      <list>
        <item>Card Sorting: Purpose is to create structure. When: Before IA exists. User task: Group items. Output: Suggested categories.</item>
        <item>Tree Testing: Purpose is to validate structure. When: After IA draft. User task: Find items. Output: Success/failure data.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="key-metrics">
      <list>
        <item>Success rate — Found correct answer. Good target: greater than 80%</item>
        <item>Directness — Found it without backtracking. Good target: greater than 70%</item>
        <item>Time to complete — How long task took. Varies by task.</item>
        <item>First click — Where users started. Should be correct category.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="step-1-create-the-tree">
      <p>Convert your IA to a text hierarchy showing all levels and their parent-child relationships:</p>
      <code lang="text"><![CDATA[Home
├── Products
│   ├── Category A
│   │   ├── Product 1
│   │   └── Product 2
│   └── Category B
│       └── Product 3
├── Support
│   ├── FAQs
│   ├── Contact Us
│   └── Returns
└── Account
    ├── Orders
    └── Settings]]></code>
      <p>Rules for creating the tree:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Use actual labels that will appear in the live navigation (no placeholder text).</item>
        <item>Include all navigation levels that users will see in the final design.</item>
        <item>Match the planned structure exactly; don't simplify or rearrange for the test.</item>
        <item>Limit to approximately 100 items total for clarity; deeper trees overwhelm participants.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="step-2-write-tasks">
      <p>Task format: "Where would you find [thing]?" Use user language, not system language. Each task should represent a realistic goal a user might have.</p>
      <p>Good tasks frame the user's intent:</p>
      <list>
        <item>"You want to return a product. Where would you go?"</item>
        <item>"Find information about shipping costs."</item>
        <item>"Look for your order history."</item>
      </list>
      <p>Bad tasks leak labels or are too directive:</p>
      <list>
        <item>"Find Returns" — gives away the exact label.</item>
        <item>"Navigate to the support section" — too directive, doesn't feel like a real user goal.</item>
      </list>
      <p>Task selection strategy:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Cover key user goals (10-15 tasks typical). Too many tasks (greater than 15) exhaust participants; too few (less than 10) miss important paths.</item>
        <item>Include different depths of navigation: some top-level, some nested 2-3 levels deep.</item>
        <item>Represent different content types: product pages, support docs, account settings, etc.</item>
        <item>Prioritize high-traffic and high-value tasks first. Use analytics or user interviews to identify the most critical flows.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="step-3-define-correct-answers">
      <p>For each task, identify where users should end up and what alternative paths are acceptable:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Correct destination(s): Where a user following the IA should successfully land.</item>
        <item>Acceptable paths: Alternative valid locations (e.g., if return info appears in multiple sections).</item>
      </list>
      <p>Example task definition:</p>
      <p>Task: "You want to check your order status"</p>
      <p>Correct: Account greater than Orders</p>
      <p>Also acceptable: Support greater than Order Status (if that section exists in your tree)</p>
      <p>Avoid: Any other path counts as a failure and should trigger analysis of why.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="step-4-run-the-test">
      <p>Participant requirements:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Sample size: 30-50 participants for statistical confidence on top-line success rate. Below 30, per-task confidence intervals are too wide to drive decisions.</item>
        <item>Representativeness: Recruit participants who match your target user demographics.</item>
        <item>Baseline: No prior knowledge of your IA. If participants are your coworkers, they'll succeed even with a bad IA.</item>
      </list>
      <p>Test logistics:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Format: Unmoderated remote testing works well and scales cheaply. Moderated thinking-aloud sessions (5-8 people) provide qualitative insight into *why* users navigate the way they do.</item>
        <item>Duration: 10-15 minutes typical. Participants fatigue after task 12-15, so cap the set.</item>
        <item>Task randomization: Shuffle task order per participant to avoid order bias.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="step-5-analyze-results">
      <p>For each task, calculate and interpret:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Success rate: What percentage of participants found the correct answer?</item>
        <item>First-click accuracy: What percentage got the first click right? (Critical signal.)</item>
        <item>Path distribution: Where did participants navigate? Did they all converge or spread?</item>
        <item>Directness: Did they backtrack or abandon?</item>
      </list>
      <p>Document failures and patterns systematically so you can iterate informed.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="step-6-iterate">
      <p>Based on findings, prioritize fixes:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Rename confusing labels if many users chose the wrong first click.</item>
        <item>Move misplaced content if success is low after the correct first click (structure issue, not label).</item>
        <item>Add cross-links if content seems to be in multiple logical homes.</item>
        <item>Retest problem areas after changes to confirm improvement.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="success-rate-guidelines">
      <p>Interpret overall and per-task success rates to decide on next steps:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Greater than 80%: Excellent, move forward to design and build.</item>
        <item>60-80%: Acceptable but needs minor fixes. Prioritize tasks below 60%.</item>
        <item>40-60%: Problem area requiring structure or label rework before launch.</item>
        <item>Less than 40%: Major issue, fundamental redesign needed.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="first-click-analysis">
      <p>First click data is the single most predictive metric:</p>
      <list>
        <item>If first click is correct: 87% likely to ultimately succeed in navigating to the answer.</item>
        <item>If first click is wrong: only 46% likely to recover and find the correct answer.</item>
      </list>
      <p>Lesson: Focus first on getting users to the right top-level category or section. If first click is wrong, they're likely lost.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="path-analysis">
      <p>When analyzing where people went wrong, look for patterns:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Common wrong paths: Indicates a label problem or structural ambiguity. Many users picked the same wrong category, so the IA needs clearer distinction.</item>
        <item>Random paths: Users are guessing. The label is too vague or doesn't match their mental model.</item>
        <item>Backtracking: The structure doesn't match user expectations. They start in one place, realize it's wrong, then navigate elsewhere.</item>
        <item>Abandonment: Content seems to not exist in the tree. Users give up because they can't find the category at all.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="limitations">
      <list>
        <item>Text-only trees strip context cues users actually rely on (icons, visual hierarchy, search, recency, recommendations).</item>
        <item>Self-selection bias: panel users are not your users; high success in tests, lower in production.</item>
        <item>Label fatigue: doesn't catch cases where users pick a "good enough" wrong answer because they're tired of exploring.</item>
        <item>Statistical power: N=30-50 stabilizes top-line success but per-task confidence intervals stay wide for low-frequency tasks.</item>
        <item>Mobile context: standard tree tests don't represent narrow viewport or swipe-based navigation.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="combining-with-other-methods">
      <p>Tree testing is one piece of a larger IA validation workflow:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Card sorting: Understand user mental models for the initial taxonomy.</item>
        <item>Create IA draft: Based on card sorting results plus business needs.</item>
        <item>Tree testing: Validate the draft before investing in visual design.</item>
        <item>Iterate: Fix problems found.</item>
        <item>Retest: Confirm improvements.</item>
        <item>Usability testing: Full design with IA plus visual hierarchy, information scent, and interactive elements.</item>
      </list>
      <p>Triangulation: Pair tree-test numbers (success rate, directness) with analytics (actual click paths from live site) and usability testing (what users say about navigation during full-design testing).</p>
    </section>

    <section name="common-mistakes">
      <list>
        <item>Testing too many levels: Keep tree to 3-4 levels max. Deeper trees overwhelm.</item>
        <item>Tasks reveal the answer: Never use exact labels from the tree in task wording. Forces participants to use memory and navigation, not text search.</item>
        <item>Too few participants: N less than 30 gives unstable results. Aim for 50 when possible.</item>
        <item>Ignoring first-click data: This is your most actionable metric.</item>
        <item>Testing without iteration: One round gives baseline; second round after fixes validates improvement.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="tools-and-services">
      <list>
        <item>Optimal Workshop Treejack: Industry standard, robust recruitment and reporting. Pricing: high.</item>
        <item>UserZoom: Enterprise features and integration. Pricing: high.</item>
        <item>PlaybookUX: Simple interface, affordable. Pricing: low to moderate.</item>
        <item>UXtweak: Good free tier plus paid features. Pricing: low.</item>
        <item>Maze: Modern interface with tree-test and first-click testing. Pricing: moderate.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>Drive an AI agent to convert an IA spec into the test tool's tree format, write tasks (without revealing labels), and define correct answer paths. Once results come back as CSV, a synthesizer agent computes per-task success/directness/first-click and clusters wrong paths. A copy agent proposes label rewrites, and the cycle re-runs until success exceeds 80%.</p>
      <p>Recommended subagents:</p>
      <list>
        <item>faion-ux-researcher-agent: task writing, correct-path definition, test plan generation.</item>
        <item>faion-usability-agent: synthesize results, recommend label and structure fixes.</item>
        <item>tree-csv-analyzer custom agent: load Treejack/UXtweak CSV export, compute per-task tables and cluster analysis.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="prompt-patterns">
      <code lang="text"><![CDATA[Given <IA YAML>, generate 12 tree-test tasks:
- Cover 3 navigation depths and 4 content types.
- Phrase as "Where would you go to <user goal>?" using user vocabulary.
- Do NOT include any tree label verbatim.
- Output JSON with task, correct path(s), acceptable alternates, priority.]]></code>
      <code lang="text"><![CDATA[Given <CSV from Treejack>, output:
- Task table: success%, directness%, median time, top-3 paths.
- Wrong-path clusters with hypothesized cause (label vs. structure vs. depth).
- Specific renames or moves to test next round.]]></code>
    </section>

    <section name="cli-tools">
      <list>
        <item>optimal-workshop API: Programmatically launch Treejack tests, pull results. https://optimalworkshop.com/api</item>
        <item>uxtweak API: Same for UXtweak Tree Testing. https://uxtweak.com/api</item>
        <item>pandas: Analyze exported CSVs. Install with `pip install pandas`</item>
        <item>jq: Quick JSON path analysis on test outputs. https://stedolan.github.io/jq</item>
        <item>csvkit: CSV slicing for first-click and path analysis. Install with `pip install csvkit`</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Run baseline test on the EXISTING IA before launching the redesign. Gives you a delta target for improvement.</item>
        <item>Aim for 50 participants per tree variant. Under 30, per-task confidence intervals are too wide.</item>
        <item>Don't paraphrase tasks across rounds. Identical wording ensures comparability and lets you detect real improvement.</item>
        <item>Pair tree testing with 5-user moderated think-aloud sessions. Numbers tell you where users navigate; qualitative tells you why.</item>
        <item>Test at most 12-15 tasks. Longer tests degrade attention after task 10.</item>
        <item>Use first-click data to triage fixes. If first click is wrong on greater than 40% of users, fix top-level labels first.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <list>
        <item>LLMs writing tasks frequently leak tree labels into the prompt. Enforce a labels-blacklist check.</item>
        <item>Auto-generated correct paths miss legitimate cross-link routes. Designer review required.</item>
        <item>LLM summaries flatten signal. Always retain raw wrong-path top-5 for human inspection.</item>
        <item>Human checkpoint: IA owner must approve label/structure changes before next test round. Agent recommendations sometimes favor removing depth, which can worsen scent.</item>
        <item>For multilingual sites, never let one agent translate tasks AND grade results. Translation drift inflates apparent success.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="test-plan-template">
      <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[# Tree Testing Plan

**Project:** [Name]
**Date:** [Date]
**IA Version:** [Version number]

## Objectives
- Validate proposed information architecture
- Identify navigation problems before development
- Compare alternative structures (if testing variants)

## Tree Structure

[Paste tree here]

## Tasks (10-15)

| # | Task | Correct Answer | Priority |
|---|------|----------------|----------|
| 1 | "You want to..." | [Path > To > Answer] | High |
| 2 | "Find where to..." | [Path > To > Answer] | High |
| 3 | | | |

## Participants
- **Target:** 50 participants
- **Criteria:** [Screening criteria]
- **Recruitment:** [Platform/method]
- **Incentive:** [Amount]

## Success Criteria
- Overall success rate: >80%
- No task below 60% success
- Directness: >70%

## Timeline
- Tree setup: [Date]
- Recruitment: [Date range]
- Data collection: [Date range]
- Analysis: [Date]
- Report: [Date]]]></code>
    </section>

    <section name="results-report-template">
      <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[# Tree Testing Results

**Test dates:** [Start] to [End]
**Participants:** [N]
**Tasks:** [N]

## Executive Summary

**Overall success rate:** [X%]
**Overall directness:** [X%]

**Key findings:**
1. [Finding 1]
2. [Finding 2]
3. [Finding 3]

## Task Results

### Task 1: "[Task description]"

**Success rate:** [X%]
**Directness:** [X%]
**Average time:** [X seconds]

**Path analysis:**
| Path taken | Count | % |
|------------|-------|---|
| Products > Category A (correct) | 40 | 80% |
| Support > FAQs | 7 | 14% |
| Account > Settings | 3 | 6% |

**First clicks:**
| Category | % of users |
|----------|------------|
| Products | 85% |
| Support | 10% |
| Account | 5% |

**Insight:** [What this tells us]
**Recommendation:** [What to do]

## Problem Areas

| Issue | Affected Tasks | Severity | Recommendation |
|-------|----------------|----------|----------------|
| [Label confusion] | 2, 5, 8 | High | [Fix] |
| [Missing category] | 3 | Medium | [Fix] |

## Recommendations

1. **High priority:**
   - [Change 1]
   - [Change 2]

2. **Consider:**
   - [Change 3]

3. **Monitor:**
   - [Area to watch]

## Appendix
- Full tree structure
- Task list
- Participant demographics
- Raw data]]></code>
    </section>

